Description.caption: Handwritten on negative: Dr. Carl Wagner|~|A cropped version of this photograph appears on a later date with the caption, Spectacular Accident Costs Two Lives Less than twenty-four house after she had seen a studio preview of her first starring picture, Dorothy Dell, screen actress and former beauty contest winner, was killed in a spectacular automobile accident in Pasadena early yesterday. Miss Dell is shown in the upper picture, with her sister, Miss Helen Dell, left, and their mother, Mrs. Lillian Goff. In the lower right-hand picture is Dr. Carl Wagner, Pasadena surgeon and driver of the car, who died several hours after the crash. Below at left is a view of the wrecked car. [Los Angeles Times, 09 Jun. 1934: A1|~|Text from negative sleeve: WAGNER, CARL DR. SEIVER [sic] MURDER CASE 1933

Description.caption: Text from newspaper caption: Figures and Scenes in Abduction Inquiry Ernest E. Noon, at the left, above, attorney for the family of William F. Gettle, kidnaped Beverly Hills millionaire, has, at the request of Mrs. Gettle and law enforcement representatives of the city and county, complete charge of the effort to have the millionaire returned safely and to pay whatever ransom the Gettle abductors demand (Associated Press photo.) In the next tier are, above, the patio of the Gettle home in Beverly Hills where press headquarters have been established during the feverish days of the case and, below, is the newly built recreation hall at the Arcadia estate from which Gettle was kidnaped. Next is Rags, blooded Scottie, a favorite of the abducted magnate, pining for the return of his master. At the right is an Associated Press photo of William F. Gettle in his Shrine uniform.|~|Text from negative sleeve: GETTLE, WILLIAM F. KIDNAP CASE 2
Description.note: A picture of a photograph of the bungalow surrounded by trees and open lawn.

Description.note: Description.note: This photograph appears with the article, "Goldstein gets term in prison: Rich Man Pleads Guilty to Killing, Stern Sentence Given on Charge of Manslaughter, Slayer Will be Taken to San Quentin Soon," Los Angeles Times, 20 Aug 1927: A5|~|Photograph misfiled and scanned with photographs from the 1933 Los Angeles Open.|~|In August of 1927, the wealthy President of the Rothschild Mortgage and Finance Company, Jacob Goldstein, was charged with murdering his business associate Frederick A.
